Lincoln JH/HS travels to Bennington for the CC Invite on Thursday, September 17, 2020, starting with JH at 3:45 p.m. Spectator guidelines established by Bennington on attendance: Spectators will be expected to use the lot SOUTH of the school building for parking.
Spectators are not allowed near the starting line, finish line, or
the team camp areas. Spectators are to remain off the football field and outside the track. Masks are not required as long as 6ft social distancing is maintained. Spectators are required to maintain their distance from ALL participants at ALL times. These are general guidelines that Bennington JH/HS will be following for the safety of not only student athletes, but also for those in attendance. Thank you.

post_text: USD 298 Lincoln offers healthy meals every school day. text: USD 298 Parents and Guardians: There was a typo on the LES enrollment letter that requires clarification. At USD 298 enrollment, masks are highly encouraged and will be available for patrons, however they are not required per current mandate at this time. USD 298 prioritizes parent, staff and student safety and will limit the numbers of individuals in the gym during enrollment, and will temperature screen all patrons to gain entry into the building. Thank you for your continued cooperation and patience at this time.

post_text:
Below are some important safety protocols that will take place at USD 298 enrollment:

All patrons entering LES will have their temperatures screened and be seated outside of the gym spaced apart for social distancing. Capacity inside the gym will be closely monitored to ensure a minimal amount of patrons at one time. Please bring your own writing utensils. Masks will be available upon entry. Only one parent for each family should attend, if possible . High school students may attend with parents to finalize schedule details. These plans are subject to approval and modification by county health officials. USD 298 is working diligently to ensure the safety of all patrons and students at this time.

post_text: Ready! Set! Call for the Count! The working parts of US Census weeklong push to increase 2020 Census self-response rates are on point thanks to a great team and partners making things happen!
text: Ready! Set! Call for the Count! The working parts of US Census weeklong push to increase 2020 Census self-response rates are on point thanks to a great team and partners making things happen!

post_text:
“To renew enthusiasm among Kansas communities, US Census planning a collaborative statewide push to engage Kansans in a “Call for the Count” week. Call for the Count” is very basic and built on the notion of a phone tree. And it’s easily done from the comfort of your home. This can be a call, a text, an email, or outreach via your favorite social media platforms!
How does it work? – Ask at least five co-workers, friends, neighbors or family members to fill out their Census form. And then ask those who agree to call five of their friends and family members. And so on. The concept is in keeping with the idea trusted voices will be the ones to convince others — especially those hard-to reach -- to fill out the Census

How does it work? – Ask at least five co-workers, friends, neighbors or family members to fill out their Census form. And then ask those who agree to call five of their friends and family members. The following students placed in the KSPA State Journalism competition.

Because of Covid-19, the contest was completely different this year with students competing from home and submitting their entry digitally a few weeks ago.

C. Walter - 3rd place in News Page Design

post_text: Look weekly on these TV stations for short, fun lessons.
shared_text:
Kansas State Department of Education
April 17 at 4:46 PM ·

We are excited to announce that Kansas teachers, students and parents just got a new partner in their continuous learning efforts.

Thanks to the support of Kansas Public Broadcasters, Kansas students will receive supplemental education content by way of a new television program produced by Kansas PBS stations and KSDE, and hosted by local teachers. The new program called Learning Across Kansas will begin airing the week of April 20.

Each 30-minute segment, individually produced for elementary, middle school and high school students, will feature grade-specific educational content delivered by our very own Kansas teachers who serve on KSDE’s Continuous Learning Task Force.

Teachers, students and parents/caregivers, tune in for short, fun and engaging lessons. Plus, you just might see one of your own teachers presenting!

Learn more by visiting, https://www.ksde.org/Agency/Fiscal-and-Administrative-Services/Communications-and-Recognition-Programs/Learning-Across-Kansas

The Lincoln USD 298 Board of Education approved the USD 298 Continuous Learning Plan (CLP) and Waiver Application for submission to the Kansas Department of Education (KSDE). District staff worked with Building Principals to develop this educational plan supporting learning and continued development of academic competences for each grade and subject level for this unique end of the school year.

KSDE staff will review and then submit the District's CLP and Waiver Application to the Kansas State Board of Education (SBOD) for final approval in mid-April. The Final Approved CPL and Waiver Application will be placed on the District's website when the SBOE provides final approval for all plans across Kansas.
Click the link for USD 298's Continuous Learning Plan
https://5il.co/ew1m

post_text:
Message from KSHSAA to all spring student athletes and their coaches:
"Effective Monday, March 16, all spring sports and activities are suspended through Sunday, March 22. This includes cancellation of all practices and competitions for this week. This prohibition is consistent with KSDE and governmental guidance and may be extended, should conditions warrant. Please note spring sports team members are prohibited from club or outside team participation and practice during this period. Not only would such outside participation be contrary to handbook rule, it would be contrary to the very reason activities are cancelled during the time we seek to mitigate potential transfer of the contagion."
